267","1245":"1245","before 1320":"před 1320","1210":"1210","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","about 1262":"okolo 1262","1290":"1290","Dinmael, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"da":{"about 1262–":"omkring 1262–Afdød","1245–Male":"1245–Afdød","1250–Male":"1250–Afdød","1262–Male":"1262–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1290–Female":"1290–Afdød","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Afdød","Abt 1250":"omkring 1250","about 1290":"omkring 1290","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","before 1320":"før 1320","1210":"1210","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","about 1262":"omkring 1262","1290":"1290","Dinmael, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"nl":{"about 1262–":"circa 1262–Overleden","1245–Male":"1245–Overleden","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1262–Male":"1262–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1290–Female":"1290–Overleden","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","Abt 1250":"circa 1250","about 1290":"circa 1290","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","before 1320":"vóór 1320","1210":"1210","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","about 1262":"circa 1262","1290":"1290","Dinmael, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wales":"Wales"},"en":{"about 1262–":"about 1262–Deceased","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1262–Male":"1262–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","Abt 1250":"about 1250","about 1290":"about 1290","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","before 1320":"before 1320","1210":"1210","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","about 1262":"about 1262","1290":"1290","Dinmael, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Owen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Owain</i>, from Latin <i>Eugenius</i> (see   Eugene  ). This Welsh personal name is cognate with Old Irish <i>Eogán</i>, see 2 and 3.","Scottish and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Eoghain</b> ‘son of <i>Eoghan</i>’. See   McEwen  .","Irish: from <b>Ó hEoghain</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Eoghan</i>’. See   Ewen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Owens","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Owen  , with post-medieval excrescent English <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form by bearers of the Gaelic surname <b>Mac Eoghain</b> (see   McEwen  )."]},{"name":"Eugene","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Gesner, Lucienne, Yanick, Alphonse, Amie, Andre, Dany, Edwige, Jean Marc, Jean-Robert, Lafontant.","French (<b>Eugène</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Eugène</b>): from the French personal name <i>Eugène</i>, Latin <i>Eugenius</i>, from Greek <i>Eugenios</i>, a derivative of <i>eugenēs</i> ‘well-born, noble’. The name <i>Eugenios</i> or <i>Eugenius</i> was borne by a 3rd-century bishop and martyr, who gave the personal name some currency during the Middle Ages, as well as by several other early Christian saints and four popes. This surname is most common in Haiti.","Americanized form of Greek patronymics from the personal name <i>Evgenios</i>, from classical Greek <i>Eugenios</i> ‘Eugene’ (see 1 above), for example <b>Evgeniadis</b> or <b>Evgenidis</b>."]}]},{"name":"Llewellyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."],"variants":[{"name":"Llywellyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]},{"name":"Llywelyn","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llewellyn ap Owen was born about 1262, his father, Owain ap Bleddyn, was 53 and his mother, Gwenllian verch Madog ap Rhirld Flaidd of Pennant Melangell, was 54. He married Mrs Llewellyn ap Owen before 1320, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1262–":"umbes 1262–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","before 1320":"enne 1320","1210":"1210","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","about 1262":"umbes 1262","1290":"1290","Dinmael, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1262–":"noin 1262–Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1262–Male":"1262–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1210–1267":"1210–1267","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","about 1290":"noin 1290","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","before 1320":"ennen vuotta 1320","121